{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_oliver_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280600568/1930110101/0378.xml":{"full_text":"ADVANCE ON CURB\nIN FINAL TRADING\nPublic Utilities First to Re\nverse Downward Trend Earl-\nHSfc- in Session.\nBY JOHN A. CRONE.\n\u2022\u00bbeelsl Dispatch to The Star.\nNEW YORK, November I.\u2014 The Curb\nMarket, after a weak opening and light\ntrading in the first \u2022hour, rallied in the\nlast few minutes today.\nPublic utilities, which had been under\npressure from the opening gong, were\nthe first to reverse their early down\nward trend. Electric Bond Share\nadvanced fractionally after losing a\npoint. Cities Service was up a shade\nfrom its low of the session and Columbia\nOil Gasoline gained near the close.\nCoppers continued to move in diverse\ndirections, domestics for the most part\ndeclining and foreign shares advancing.\nUnited Verde held firm, however, in\nthe face of September production of\n3,771,274 pounds against 4.028.442 in\nAugust. The company reports cash on\nhand October 1 at $998,762. Invest\nments were carried at $5.096 897, but\nhad a market value October 1 of $3,-\n884,012.\nAttempts to bring about a huge consoli\ndation of African copper companies ac\ncount for the firmness of foreign cop\nper issues. Merger proosals Involve\nthe Rhodesian Selection Trust. Congo\nBorder Mining and B' Wana M\u2019 Kuba\nCorporation. The American Metal Co.\nhere is interested in Rhodesian and\nB* Wana M\u2019 Kuba, both of which are ac\ntive here, while Rhodesian has large\nholdings in Roan Antelope Copper,\nwhich has been firm in the last sev\neral sessions.\nGulf Oil of Pennsylvania early in\nthe session came within a fraction of its\nrecord low level. Derby Oil Refining\neased when its various subsidiaries\nshowed third-quarter profits of $218,-\n151, against $361,177 In the preceding\nquarter.\nRadio shares, both communication\nand manufacturing companies, showed\nslight firming tendencies, but trading In\nthem remained small.\nSTOCK AVERAGES DROP\nUNDER LOWS OF YEAR\n\u25a0\u2022eclal Dispatch to The Star.\nNEW YORK, November I.\u2014All of\nthe price average tables today indicate\nthat the stock market has broken well\nbelow the range of October 22 and is\nIn a region where, speculatively, it\nwill have to meet further severe tests.\nProm the high average level early in\nOctober prices dropped an average of\nnearly 40 points to the closing of the\nmonth. The public utilities are still\nslightly above their average figure of\n10 days ago.\nThe effect of this is to produce more\nliquidation by tired holders of stocks,\nwho want cash rather than securities.\nIt also encourages more short-selling.\nA majority of brokers\u2019 letters today em\nphasized the probability of lower prices\nprior to election, with comment reserved\nconcerning the outlook beyond that\ndate, as this depends somewhat on how\nthe country will receive the election re\nsults.\nBONDS ON THE CURB\nMARKET.\nDOMESCnC BONDS.\nBales. High. Low. Close.\n4 Alabama Pw 4%s \u201967 98\u2019. 98% 98%\n1 Alabama Pow Ss |66 101 V. 101% 101%\n4 Aluminum Co 5a 52 103% 103\u2019* 103%\n5 Aluminum Ltd 5s \u20194B 99% 99% 99*\u00ab\n5Am Cmwlh Pw Ss '4O 91\u2019. 91 91*.\n1 Amer G A E 5s \u20192B. 98*4 98% 98*4\njAmer G i Pow Ss \u201939 94% 94% 94%\n14 Amer P*L Ss 2016.. 107 106% 107\n1 Appalach Gas Ss 45. 89 89 S 3 I\n1 Arkana P A L 5s ;56 100% 100*4 100*.\n1 Armstr'g Cork 5s '4O 97\u2018a 97'a 97>s\n1 Asao Electric 4%s 53 90 90 90\n$5 A\u00bbSO GA E 4%s 49 C 77% 76% 77\n17 Asso Gas A El 5s 'SO 84*. 84% 84 i\n11 Asso Gas A El 5s \u2019BB 83 82% 83\n12 As OAE sVs* '3B In cf 81 81 4 81%\n4 ASSO GA E s'as \u201877. 95% 95'4 95*4\nlAsTfl Util 5%s \u201944 C 90\u2019, 90\u2019. 90\u2019.\n7 Bell Tel Can 6s A '55 104 104 104\nSBell Tel Can 5s B '57 104 104 104\n6Can Nat Ry 4*48 '55 101% 101% 101%\n2 Can Nat RE7s E '35 108 a 108 108\n17 Cap Adm 5s 53 xw.. S2\u2018/a 81% 82%\nCent Stat Elec 5s '4B 71 71 71\nt Chi Dis Elec 5%s '3O 100% 100 100%\nIChic Ry cod 5s